all_recipes.name: How to make beef stock
all_recipes.description: Essential to hearty soups and sauces, make a big batch of beef stock and freeze it in ice cube trays..

all_recipes.name: Chickpea and chestnut stuffing
all_recipes.description: Free from: wheat, gluten, dairy, soya and egg

all_recipes.name: Sandwich bread loaf
all_recipes.description: Milk, butter and golden syrup makes this loaf particularly rich and delicious, and it keeps well too

all_recipes.name: Cherry meringues with rhubarb coulis
all_recipes.description: Master the art of how to make meringues with Michel Roux Snr.

all_recipes.name: Pear pavlovas with chocolate sauce
all_recipes.description: Chewy discs of meringue topped with poached pears, vanilla cream and chocolate sauce - a real showstopper!

all_recipes.name: Oatmeal and hazelnut meringues with raspberries and cream
all_recipes.description: This is a sophisticated twist on classic cranachan and would make an impressive end to a dinner party.

all_recipes.name: Cornmeal pudding with sultanas and coconut
all_recipes.description: This recipe was cooked by amateur chefs as part of the BBC's Step Up to the Plate television programme.

all_recipes.name: Daiquiri
all_recipes.description: Unwind with a refreshing daiquiri – a classic Cuban cocktail.

all_recipes.name: Versailles shake
all_recipes.description: Why just use rhubarb in desserts? Lengths of the pink stuff can perk up cocktails as well.

all_recipes.name: Meringues with summer berries
all_recipes.description: Pillow soft and feather light, a meringue with fresh berries is the epitome of a summer dessert.

all_recipes.name: Homemade custard
all_recipes.description: There's nothing like homemade custard to go with crumble, pies and stewed fruit - it's much nicer than ready-made varieties

all_recipes.name: Apple crumble
all_recipes.description: This recipe is an all-time favourite of those hankering after the ultimate quick and easy dessert. Serve with nostalgia.

all_recipes.name: Baby bruschettas with poached pears, gorgonzola and port syrup
all_recipes.description: It is really important that the pears are firm for this recipe, or they will fall apart when you poach them. Poaching the pears can be done the night before.This also allows the syrup to cool and thicken.

all_recipes.name: Green herb frittatas with chunky tomato salsa
all_recipes.description: Individual frittatas, made with fresh parsley and chives, served with ripe tomato salsa, packed with basil.

all_recipes.name: Quick tomato and basil tart
all_recipes.description: Make this simple tart in the summer when tomatoes are at their best. Serve with a green salad for a quick lunch.

all_recipes.name: Stilton and toasted walnut balls
all_recipes.description: These easy Stilton and walnut balls make great Christmas nibbles.

all_recipes.name: Cherry tomato, marinated feta and basil skewers
all_recipes.description: A little tomato and feta skewer makes an easy vegetarian nibble that fits in at any buffet party.

all_recipes.name: Stir fried chicken with black bean sauce
all_recipes.description: A popular and easy stir-fry, chicken and black bean sauce is a great midweek supper.

all_recipes.name: Kerala king prawn and coconut curry
all_recipes.description: This quick prawn curry is the perfect blend of spicy, fresh and creamy. And it takes minutes to make.

all_recipes.name: Daal saag
all_recipes.description: A really simple, but really good daal recipe. Make a big batch and freeze any leftovers.

all_recipes.name: Aubergine fritters with tomato chutney
all_recipes.description: This recipe was cooked by amateur chefs as part of the BBC's Step Up to the Plate television programme.

all_recipes.name: Prawns in tomato sauce served with rice and red lentils
all_recipes.description: This recipe was cooked by amateur chefs as part of the BBC's Step Up to the Plate television programme.

all_recipes.name: Classic carrot cake
all_recipes.description: Nothing beats a classic carrot cake - this one has a touch of cinnamon and walnuts.

all_recipes.name: Apple compôte
all_recipes.description: Apple compôte is a great way to use up a glut of apples, and makes a delicious breakfast or healthy dessert.

all_recipes.name: Rice pudding with rhubarb compôte
all_recipes.description: Clotted cream, vanilla and a rhubarb compôte take this school dinner classic to another level.

all_recipes.name: Pan fried scallops with caramelised cauliflower purée and cumin velouté
all_recipes.description: Scallops and cauliflower is a surprisingly good combination, served here with a creamy cumin sauce that's sure to impress.

all_recipes.name: Curried carrot soup
all_recipes.description: This lightly spiced carrot soup couldn't be any simpler to make, yet it makes a delicious supper on a cold winter's evening.

all_recipes.name: Wild mushroom soup
all_recipes.description: Use a mixture of wild mushrooms to make this luxurious soup with the flavour of autumn.

all_recipes.name: Beef, oyster and ale pie
all_recipes.description: A beautifully balanced recipe for beef, oyster and ale pie with flavours of tarragon, dark ale, bacon.

all_recipes.name: Baked heritage carrots with pan-fried scallops
all_recipes.description: Michael Caines' sophisticated recipe is a real celebration of carrots. Try to use the best quality carrots you can get.

all_recipes.name: Smoked salmon kedgeree
all_recipes.description: This tasty salmon kedgeree with homemade watercress hollandaise is perfect for a smart brunch.

all_recipes.name: Barbecued lamb with summer slaw and potato wedges
all_recipes.description: This is the perfect barbecue recipe: slow-cooked ribs, lamb chops and spiced lamb kebabs served with potato wedges and homemade coleslaw. Remember to soak your wooden skewers in cold water.

all_recipes.name: Chocolate and salted caramel torte
all_recipes.description: These individual tortes are served with a salted caramel sauce and homemade ice cream. Buy the ice cream instead of making it from scratch and this recipe can be ready in 30 minutes.

all_recipes.name: Rhubarb and honeycomb trifle
all_recipes.description: Rhubarb poached in ginger and lime, mixed into a trifle with sponge and honeycomb spinkled cream.

all_recipes.name: Almond crusted red mullet, fennel and blood orange salad
all_recipes.description: Red mullet fillets, served with a luxurious fennel and blood orange salad, fennel purée and crushed new potatoes.

all_recipes.name: Duck with a cherry purée, rosti potatoes, spinach and a port jus
all_recipes.description: Delicious duck breast with a sweet and sharp cherry sauce, wilted spinach and rosti potatoes.

all_recipes.name: Classic rich chocolate sauce
all_recipes.description: Serve this warm chocolate sauce over vanilla ice cream, meringues or even as a chocolate fondue.

all_recipes.name: Apple and passion fruit tartlets
all_recipes.description: These crisp, custardy tartlets with fragrant sharp passion fruit are sure to win any girl's heart. They make a good breakfast, too!

all_recipes.name: Crêpes with orange butter sauce
all_recipes.description: Fragrant with orange blossom water, these buttery citrus pancakes make a beautiful dessert.

all_recipes.name: Poached pears in Sauternes
all_recipes.description: This classy dessert from Michel Roux is delicious, low in fat, and counts as one of your 5-a-day!

all_recipes.name: Chicken terrine with herbs
all_recipes.description: These terrines are perfect for keeping in the fridge over the festive period for an impromptu snack. They’d be delicious with a pear, fig chutney or Cumberland sauce.

all_recipes.name: Poussin scented with ginger and lemongrass
all_recipes.description: Tender young chicken cooked with fragrant Thai flavours, served with deep fried rocket. If there is any chicken and rice left over, shred the chicken, fold it into the rice and serve with soy sauce and wasabi on the side.

all_recipes.name: Madeleines
all_recipes.description: Bake a batch of these buttery little French cakes to have with a cup of tea or coffee.

all_recipes.name: Fruit tarts
all_recipes.description: Serve these fruit tarts alongside a selection of other cakes and sandwiches cut into triangles for a delicious afternoon tea.

all_recipes.name: Spiced red wine strawberry compôte
all_recipes.description: This recipe for strawberries cooked with red wine and spices is well worth a try.

all_recipes.name: Iced strawberry nougat
all_recipes.description: Michel Roux's impressive strawberry dessert can be made ahead of time and kept in the freezer until ready to serve.

all_recipes.name: Floating islands
all_recipes.description: My favourite dessert as a child and one that was made as a real treat was oeufs à la neige, floating islands. The smell of caramel cooking always brings back childhood memories.

all_recipes.name: French apple tart with calvados and Chantilly cream
all_recipes.description: Use bought puff pastry to make this easy apple tart laced with calvados and topped with soft Chantilly – look out for all-butter puff for the best flavour.

all_recipes.name: Poached peaches with zabaglione
all_recipes.description: Zabaglione is an Italian custard, served here in layers with poached peaches and crushed amaretti biscuits. Delizioso!

all_recipes.name: Pear tart with Stilton and pistachios
all_recipes.description: You could cook the pastry and pears well in advance and assemble these gorgeous individual tarts just before you serve.

all_recipes.name: Soufflé Suissesse
all_recipes.description: This light-as-air soufflé served in a creamy Swiss-cheese sauce makes an impressive winter starter.

all_recipes.name: Roux family shepherd’s pie with stir-fried cabbage
all_recipes.description: Roast lamb was a real favourite at home on a Sunday not because of the actual roast but because the leftover was always made into my sister’s and my favourite, shepherd’s pie.

all_recipes.name: Wild boar ragù with fresh pasta
all_recipes.description: Meltingly tender wild boar, stewed in rich tomato and red wine sauce. Served with fresh, homemade tagliatelle.

all_recipes.name: Duck burger and chips
all_recipes.description: This is a burger like no other: a melting scoop of Vacherin cheese encased in minced duck meat and served in a brioche bun with girolle mushrooms. Delish.

all_recipes.name: 'No butter' brandy butter
all_recipes.description: Free from: dairy, gluten, wheat, nuts and eggs

all_recipes.name: Mussel stew with garlic
all_recipes.description: Homemade aïoli thickens and adds irresistible garlicky flavour to this delicious seafood stew. Use bread to mop up all the lovely juices - slightly stale is best as it will hold together better.

all_recipes.name: Gluten-free mince pies
all_recipes.description: These speciality mince pies are perfect for those who suffer from wheat, gluten and nut allergies, and can be dairy, soya and egg-free.

all_recipes.name: Gluten-free Christmas cake
all_recipes.description: This Christmas cake ensures everyone can have a slice. Free from wheat, gluten, and soya; can be dairy, egg and nut free.

all_recipes.name: Lemon sultana cake
all_recipes.description: Free from: wheat and nuts; can be dairy, egg and soya free; no added sugar

all_recipes.name: Christmas pudding ice cream
all_recipes.description: Free from: wheat, gluten, egg and nuts free; can be dairy and soya free

all_recipes.name: Christmas pudding
all_recipes.description: Free from: dairy, wheat, gluten and soya; can be egg and nut free; no added sugar

all_recipes.name: Gluten-free chocolate and pear torte
all_recipes.description: This recipe is free from wheat, gluten and eggs and can be adapted to be free from dairy, soya and nuts!

all_recipes.name: Roasted chickpeas with nuts and/or seeds
all_recipes.description: You can use any selection of nuts and seeds that you fancy or, if you have a nut allergic guest, leave out the nuts and double up on the number of seeds. Free from: dairy, wheat, gluten, soya and eggs; can be nut-free

all_recipes.name: Seedy pastry squares
all_recipes.description: These delicious little biscuits can be used as cocktail snacks with a drink or as a biscuit with soup or cheese. Free from: wheat, gluten, soya and nuts; can be dairy and egg free

all_recipes.name: Pot roast beef with red cabbage
all_recipes.description: Free from: dairy, wheat, gluten, soya, egg and nuts

all_recipes.name: Turkey roasted in honey
all_recipes.description: Coating your turkey in honey produces a beautifully white meat with a dramatic dark skin. Free from: dairy, wheat, and gluten; can be soya, nut and egg-free

all_recipes.name: Buckwheat noodles with smoked salmon and dill
all_recipes.description: Free from: wheat, gluten, egg and nut; can be dairy and soya free.

all_recipes.name: Gooey chocolate fondant puddings
all_recipes.description: We show you how to make the ultimate gooey-centred chocolate puddings. Serve with softly whipped cream or a scoop of ice cream.

all_recipes.name: Braised red cabbage with apples and sherry vinegar
all_recipes.description: This goes brilliantly with almost any winter dish you care to mention. It takes minutes to prepare, then two hours of gentle cooking - you need do nothing except have a glass of wine and relax.

all_recipes.name: Roast potatoes
all_recipes.description: Fluffy within, crisp without and flavoured with thyme and garlic, these potatoes are a perfect sidekick to any roast.

all_recipes.name: Dauphinoise potatoes
all_recipes.description: These creamy, garlicky potatoes make a fabulous side dish for any Sunday roast.

all_recipes.name: Yorkshire pudding
all_recipes.description: Perfect Yorkshire puddings are all about making sure the fat is hot enough before you add the batter.

all_recipes.name: Easy chicken liver pâté
all_recipes.description: This starter is simple and quick to make and is absolutely delicious on toast with a spot of spicy chutney.

all_recipes.name: Roast beef and Yorkshire pudding
all_recipes.description: Find out how to roast beef to succulent perfection. Serve with our easy Yorkshire pudding.

all_recipes.name: How to roast pork loin with crackling
all_recipes.description: The combination of juicy sweet roast pork and tooth-shatteringly crisp crackling is a dream come true.

all_recipes.name: How to roast chicken
all_recipes.description: Serve with a green salad and some crusty bread in summer or with roast potatoes, carrots and peas for winter – roast chicken is a dish for all seasons.

all_recipes.name: Pork with dried fruit
all_recipes.description: Dried fruit and cider are the perfect foil for pork in this simple but delicious dish.

all_recipes.name: All things duck
all_recipes.description: Make the most of an entire bird cooked various ways with a myriad of delicious ingredients.

all_recipes.name: Roast beef, Yorkshire pudding, roast potatoes, carrots, cabbage, gravy and horseradish sauce
all_recipes.description: Beef fillet, the tenderest cut, is used in this classic Sunday roast. You could use a cheaper cut of meat, in which case amend the cooking time accordingly.

all_recipes.name: Caramelised rice pudding with spiced plum compôte
all_recipes.description: Matt Tebbutt spices up this comfort food classic with a tasty plum compôte – great for using up plums when they’re in season.

all_recipes.name: Strawberry bavarois with champagne jelly, vanilla ice cream and shortbread
all_recipes.description: A fresh basil syrup is an inspired pairing with this strawberry dessert, which is garnished with some delicate tuiles.

all_recipes.name: Panettone soufflé
all_recipes.description: A wonderful way to incorporate festive flavours into a light and sophisticated dessert.

all_recipes.name: Halva served with mango lassi
all_recipes.description: This recipe was cooked by amateur chefs as part of the BBC's Step Up to the Plate television programme.

all_recipes.name: Chocolate and chilli buns
all_recipes.description: Chocolate and chilli make a surprisingly good match in these quirky buns. Try spreading them with unsalted butter.

all_recipes.name: Proper apple pie
all_recipes.description: This is apple pie like mum used to make, with large pieces of Bramley apple enclosed in rich shortcrust pastry. Douse in cream and get stuck in.

all_recipes.name: Orange and praline croquembouche with cardamom caramel
all_recipes.description: This towering pile of choux pastry is much simpler to create than it seems. Most of it can be prepared in advance and assembled on the day.

all_recipes.name: Raspberry rose Danishes, praline spirals and Alsatian plaited Danish pastries
all_recipes.description: Danish pastry dough is very versatile and keeps well in the fridge for at least 24 hours. Use these recipes to inspire your own variations.

all_recipes.name: The midnight meringue
all_recipes.description: This decadent dessert would make an impressive finish to a dinner party. You could bake the tart case and make the filling ahead of time and whip up the meringue at the last minute.

all_recipes.name: Chocolate and orange mousse cake
all_recipes.description: Joconde is an elaborate technique to imprint decoration in a sponge. Here it is used to to adorn a rich mousse cake.

all_recipes.name: Chocolate and raspberry two-tier opera cake
all_recipes.description: This recipe for the classic Parisian gateau requires a little skill but is well worth the effort.

all_recipes.name: Fruit tarts with elderflower custard
all_recipes.description: These pretty petits fours make the best of our finest summer fruits. Ripe peaches and apricots would also work well.

all_recipes.name: Lemon and ginger millefeuilles
all_recipes.description: Once you've mastered the art of the rough puff pastry here, experiment with the fillings using your favourite flavour combinations.

all_recipes.name: Mini Black Forest meringues with everlasting syllabub
all_recipes.description: 'Everlasting syllabub' is so called because it keeps well for several hours before serving. If you make the meringue the day before, assembling these petits fours will be quick and easy.

all_recipes.name: Strawberry and rhubarb mini cheesecakes
all_recipes.description: Wow your friends with these stunning little petits fours. You could use the same recipe to make one large cheesecake.

all_recipes.name: Medley of kebabs with mint and yoghurt dressing
all_recipes.description: This recipe was cooked by amateur chefs as part of the BBC's Step Up to the Plate television programme.

all_recipes.name: Rainbow chicken curry served with pilau rice and yoghurt raita
all_recipes.description: This recipe was cooked by amateur chefs as part of the BBC's Step Up to the Plate television programme.

all_recipes.name: White currant and whisky semifreddo
all_recipes.description: These semifreddos are made a day in advance so make a stress-free but stunning end to a special meal.

all_recipes.name: Cherry clafoutis with star anise-poached cherries
all_recipes.description: Try this classic dessert with a twist, perfect for a summer dinner party.

all_recipes.name: Beef tartare with beef consommé and summer vegetables
all_recipes.description: Steak tartare looks and sounds impressive but is really easy to make. This one is spiced with a hint of fragrant star anise.

all_recipes.name: Cucumber soup with pickled cucumber
all_recipes.description: Use up a glut of cucumbers with this spicy take on cucumber soup, topped with sweet-and-sour cucumbers.

all_recipes.name: Mutton shoulder tagine
all_recipes.description: Slow cooking produces meltingly tender mutton and a crowd pleasing tagine.

all_recipes.name: Lambs’ liver with balsamic sauce
all_recipes.description: Lambs’ liver is a tasty, economical cut, used here in a quick recipe that's full of flavour.

all_recipes.name: The Great British faggot
all_recipes.description: Faggots are a cheap and delicious dish, especially served with mash and mushy peas. You’ll need a mincer for this recipe and a good butcher.

all_recipes.name: Steak and kidney pudding
all_recipes.description: Matt Tebbutt's Steak and kidney pudding is labour of love, but well worth the effort. Serve with steamed greens for rib-sticking winter supper.

all_recipes.name: Sumac and thyme-roasted chicken with saffron jus, paprika roasted potatoes and garlic beans
all_recipes.description: The fruity tartness of sumac, a delicious Middle Eastern spice, works brilliantly with chicken. Try it in place of salt or lemon juice in other recipes.

all_recipes.name: Pasta con le sarde (pasta with sardines)
all_recipes.description: Turn inexpensive fresh sardines and store cupboard ingredients into this authentic and simple Sicilian pasta dish.

all_recipes.name: Penne al'arrabiata (pasta with a tomato and chilli sauce)
all_recipes.description: Hot, quick and tasty - an easy storecupboard pasta dish for a weeknight supper.

all_recipes.name: Bara brith
all_recipes.description: Bara brith (literally “mottled bread”) is sometimes made with yeast but Mary’s family recipe omits it, giving a wonderfully sticky texture. It is best spread with plenty of butter.

all_recipes.name: Brandy butter
all_recipes.description: Use any left over brandy butter on muffins or as a sponge sandwich filling with added chopped stem ginger or delicious on crumpets.

all_recipes.name: Lomo saltado with chips
all_recipes.description: A traditional Peruvian dish, flash-fried spicy steak is served with rice and chips. Bring on the pisco sours!

all_recipes.name: Chocolate dipped chocolate shortbread
all_recipes.description: Bake a batch of melt-in-your mouth chocolate shortbread for your Red Nose Day bake sale and watch the money roll in.

all_recipes.name: Spiced summer fruits with ginger shortbread and mint cream
all_recipes.description: This recipe was cooked by amateur chefs as part of the BBC's Step Up to the Plate television programme.

all_recipes.name: Homemade chorizo
all_recipes.description: Homemade chorizo is easy to make and so much tastier than shop-bought versions. You’ll need a manual sausage machine for this recipe.

all_recipes.name: Heather honey cranachan
all_recipes.description: A traditional, harvest time, Scottish desert now served at weddings, festivals and feasts.

all_recipes.name: Langoustines with oyster mayonnaise, wilted spinach and anchovy sand
all_recipes.description: This recipe celebrates the fresh flavours of the sea and makes an indulgent starter for four or main for two.

all_recipes.name: Dutch croquettes
all_recipes.description: Kroketten are a traditional Dutch snack food, often served with French fries. This authentic recipe takes some time but the results are far better than anything you can buy ready-made.

all_recipes.name: Hungarian pork stew
all_recipes.description: This stew pairs pork and paprika beautifully. Serve with creamy mashed potato and lightly pickled cucumber.

all_recipes.name: Gluten-free apple and almond cake
all_recipes.description: This is an elegant, moist apple cake to be served in slim slices with a very fine cup of tea. It freezes brilliantly, too.

all_recipes.name: Stuffed cabbage
all_recipes.description: Delicious served with soured cream and crusty bread on the side to mop up the juices, and a cheap recipe to make too.

all_recipes.name: Dutch pea soup
all_recipes.description: A really thick and warming winter soup that can be served as a meal in itself. It freezes really well, too.

all_recipes.name: Tamarind-baked back ribs with stuffed baked onions
all_recipes.description: Delicious tamarind marinated pork, slow roasted, served with mince-filled baked red onions.

all_recipes.name: Dover sole with crab-crushed Jersey Royals and sauce grenoble
all_recipes.description: This dinner party dish looks magnificent on the plate: a neat arrangement of crab and potatoes topped with a stack of Dover sole, covered in a buttery sauce.

all_recipes.name: Poached 'cannelloni' of skate with pea risotto, asparagus and morels
all_recipes.description: This fresh spring recipe uses the best of seasonal ingredients; asparagus, peas, morels - coupled with skate wings.

all_recipes.name: Pan-roasted fillet of beef with lobster ravioli and spring vegetables
all_recipes.description: A showy, high-class dish to impress your friends, combining tender beef fillet and succulent lobster.

all_recipes.name: Chorizo tapas
all_recipes.description: These tapas make the most of the chorizo’s smoky flavour. All they need is some bread, slices of Manchego cheese and a glass of sherry.

all_recipes.name: Squid with oriental dressing
all_recipes.description: This is a really quick starter or light supper dish. The zingy sauce will really get your tastebuds going.

all_recipes.name: Mackerel pasty with watercress
all_recipes.description: These delicious mackerel pasties served with a fresh cucumber salad are perfect for summery lunch.

all_recipes.name: Spiced mackerel with horseradish potatoes
all_recipes.description: Try this lovely dish of fresh, inexpensive mackerel with a creamy potato salad, perfect for a simple supper or lunch.

all_recipes.name: Christmas Eve pasta
all_recipes.description: Make this simple pasta with broccoli, anchovies, chilli and garlic to keep Christmas Eve stress-free and flavour-packed.

all_recipes.name: Hive cake
all_recipes.description: This gorgeous lemon and honey flavoured cake with cute smiley bees buzzing round would make a perfect birthday cake.

all_recipes.name: Curried guinea fowl and lemon and saffron rice, with coriander and lime raita
all_recipes.description: This recipe was cooked by amateur chefs as part of the BBC's Step Up to the Plate television programme.

all_recipes.name: Real proper custard
all_recipes.description: Try making Mary Berry’s foolproof, homemade custard, perfect for slathering on crumbles, pies and puddings.

all_recipes.name: Mary Berry’s Simnel cake
all_recipes.description: Decorate this traditional Easter cake with crystallised primroses or other edible spring flowers to make it look extra special.

all_recipes.name: Easter biscuits
all_recipes.description: Make Easter biscuits the Mary Berry way: use half of the dough to make traditional fruited Easter biscuits, and half to make iced Easter biscuits in funky shapes.

all_recipes.name: Easter lemon pavlova
all_recipes.description: If you’re looking for something different for an Easter dessert, this stunning pavlova from Mary Berry should do the trick: lemon curd pavolva topped with mini-mounds of meringue and chocolate eggs.

all_recipes.name: Easter Simnel cake
all_recipes.description: Simnel cake was traditionally given by servant girls to their mothers when they returned home on Mothering Sunday.

all_recipes.name: Traditional Christmas pudding with brandy butter
all_recipes.description: Loaded with big pieces of fruit, Mary Berry's Christmas pudding recipe will win over the harshest critics.

all_recipes.name: Mary Berry’s mother’s bread and butter pudding
all_recipes.description: A great family favourite as pudding to follow a weekend lunch. I have to admit, the recipe is not economical – just delicious! Ideally use a rectangular dish simply because the bread fits it better. If you are not keen on sultanas, just leave them out.

all_recipes.name: Celebration chocolate cake
all_recipes.description: A moist chocolate cake that really can’t go wrong and keeps well for birthday parties. It has a wonderful white chocolate icing so the contrast looks stunning too.

all_recipes.name: Honeycomb crunchies
all_recipes.description: Honeycomb is the most amazing stuff  – add the bicarbonate of soda to the sugar and watch as it explodes in the pan and grows before your eyes. The honeycomb is then mixed with melted chocolate, syrup and biscuits to make a sticky, crunchy square.

all_recipes.name: Classic crème caramel
all_recipes.description: Mary Berry's simple step-by-step guide to the perfect crème caramel.

all_recipes.name: Christmas apricot and chestnut stuffing
all_recipes.description: It’s definitely worth the effort of making your own stuffing for Christmas dinner, and Mary Berry’s version is a winner.

all_recipes.name: Spring minestrone soup with pesto
all_recipes.description: This light and summery soup makes the most of springtime vegetables, don't forget a dollop of pesto on top.

all_recipes.name: Goats’ cheese, pepper and thyme galettes with onion marmalade
all_recipes.description: Prepare the marmalade and peppers in advance so last minute work is minimal. Serve with with a dressed mixed leaf salad.

all_recipes.name: Salmon fillet with fresh sorrel and spinach sauce
all_recipes.description: Sorrel has a sharp, crisp taste and is delicious with spinach. The base for the sauce can be made a day ahead; just reheat gently when ready to serve and add the spinach and sorrel.

all_recipes.name: Mary Berry's fish pie
all_recipes.description: Mary Berry’s mother Marjorie cooked this every year on Christmas Eve. Mary still does it today with happy memories of childhood. Make it up to 36 hours ahead before cooking and keep in the fridge.

all_recipes.name: Mary Berry’s lasagne al forno
all_recipes.description: This is a classic lasagne recipe which has been perfected over the years. For the best results leave the lasagne to stand for six hours before cooking.

all_recipes.name: Stuffed shoulder of lamb
all_recipes.description: In 1966 one of Mary Berry’s first articles for Housewife included roast stuffed veal as the main course for four people. This version of the recipe uses a boned shoulder of lamb instead.

all_recipes.name: Baked salmon with parmesan and parsley crust
all_recipes.description: Mary Berry's fooproof recipe for easy baked salmon with luscious crunchy parmesan crust can be on the table in no time.

all_recipes.name: Welsh cakes
all_recipes.description: Welsh cakes are a traditional tea-time treat that are really easy to make. Eat them warm from the stove, or store in an airtight container for up to a week.

all_recipes.name: Monkfish tail with blackened spices, purple sprouting broccoli and slightly spiced mussels

recipes.name: "Pantry Raid" Chicken Enchilada Casserole
recipes.description: "I made this recipe up one night when I had no idea what to do with a pound and a half of chicken tenderloins. It came out so well that my husband and I finished off the leftovers the next day and we are not usually leftover eaters. I am gluten-free so I used gluten-free cornbread mix. You will definitely enjoy it!"Yum.  OH!  I made this as a one-dish crockpot recipe and it was delicious.  I used chicken breasts, not tenders, adding them raw to the seasoned tomato sauce mixture and cooking it all on LO for 3.5 hrs (less for tenders).  After adding in the rest and topping with the corn muffin mix, I cooked on HI for 1.5 hours.  Next time I'll add diced onion (1 sm) and 1-2 cloves minced garlic to the tomato sauce mixture, but even as is, this was great, and a keeper.  Thanks for posting!This recipe would've been great if I had followed the original recipe.  I followed the review that recommended I cook it in the crock pot.  After 5 hours, it was complete mush!  We dipped tortilla chips in it, but it was a little much to call it a main dish.  Next time I will follow the original recipe.  The flavors were great, but a little sweet.  I may look for a corn bread mix without sugar.This was so simple and fantastic!  I added red bell pepper, onion, and minced garlic; and substituted Costco rotisserie chicken pulled off the bone.  oohlala!This was easy and delicious. I didn't even  brown the chicken first. Just simmered it with the tomato sauce. My family loved it.I made this last night and thought it was great! I added some sauteed ingredients (a large minced onion, corn, chopped mixed bell pepper strips). I also added a can of Ro-Tel diced tomatoes and green chiles. I omitted the water and just used the juice from the Ro-Tel can. Lastly, I added about a teaspoon of cumin. I know it sounds like a lot of changes but at the end of the day, the basis of this recipe is great. Don't be afraid of the 1 1/2 T of chili powder. I thought it would be quite spicy with that much but it wasn't at all and I added the Ro-Tel too! Don't be afraid to continue what started this recipe in the first place...the pantry raid!This was awesome.  I would give it 10 stars if I could.  For me this is pure comfort food; and it is so easy.  I cheated and used shredded rotisserie chicken, light cream cheese and substituted my customized Grandmother's Buttermilk Cornbread recipe with corn and jalapeños from this site instead of the cornbread mix.  So it was a super fast dinner.   Thanks for sharing a great recipe.This made a delicious and hearty meal. The only changes that I made were to use 2 cans of chicken, browned with onions and a tsp. minced garlic.  My family loved this one. I will definitely make it again.I made this tonight, and I didn't change one thing.  My husband asked for seconds and he is a picky eater. I loved the corn bread topping.

recipes.name: 100 Percent Whole Wheat Bread
recipes.description: "Nice soft whole wheat bread with added grains. Makes a 2 large loaves. Double recipe for 3 smaller loaves."So delicious!! I couldn't find vital wheat gluten, so I omitted it, but it turned out great anyway. I also added more water in the kneading process. Great recipe, thanks for sharing!should have read the reviews first, but the water/flour ratio is off.  I am somewhat new at bread and kept thinking that I was not doing something right, but it was the ratios.This is great bread! I had to make some omissions based on what I had handy (no sesame, sunflower seeds or coconut oil. I tossed in some wheat germ instead - otherwise followed the recipe except for the shape...I got 6 sandwich rolls and 1 large bunny loaf out of this. Thanks for the recipe!One detail:  If you've had breast cancer that was estrogen-receptor positive, you should avoid flax seed and flax meal.  Either leave them out, or add more of the other seeds.Let me preface this by saying I am just starting to bake bread.  It is very difficult to find a recipe with 100% whole wheat.  The only modification I made to this recipe was to add an additional 4 Tbls water as I could not get my dough to form without. I just pulled it out of the oven and my husband and I both enjoyed a slice.  Great flavor and not too dense.  Next time I am going to try using just vitamin C and omit at least some of the wheat gluten.  Thanks for sharing a great recipe for healthy bread!This was my first time attempting bread and it came out great!  I didn't have the flax seeds (added a bit extra flax seed meal) or the coconut oil (substituted toasted sesame oil) and needed to add a bit more water to get the dough to form. Tried to use my kitchenaid mixer but ended up just making it smoke -- so did all kneading by hand.  I didn't knead for full times because I got tired, but it still came out great.   The bread was a big hit and now I'm going to use it for french toast.The bread was tasty and good for sandwiches but the flour / water content was off. I used more water and approximately 5 1/2 c flour.The bread turned out beautiful.  I did have to use 2 cups of water  instead of 1/34.  Also when you cover it, don't put saran wrap on it, it will stick. It was so good.  I will make it again.

recipes.name: "Spa"ctacular Frozen Grapes
recipes.description: "These grapes were served to me after a massage at my local spa. This recipe is perfect as an after-school snack, a simple appetizer at parties, or a sweet treat before bed. Substitute Splenda® for the sugar if you like! Can be kept in a sealed bag in the freezer for several months.""Spectacular" little recipe! Ya just gotta love it when a few items you have laying around the kitchen turn into something a little extra special...  I've frozen fruit before, but never grapes. And while they're delicious with or without sugar - that addition gave regular 'ol grapes a little pizzaz.  I did use less sugar than called for and opted for Spenda which made the amount even less.  This was so easy and tasted oh so good - very nice little treat without any guilt.No sweetener necessary, even for kids' tastes, and certainly "spa"-healthier without! Frozen grapes are awesome just by themselves... They're like little natural popsicles!You can also use Sugar Free Jello for an added flavor.Never mind the sugar and put them on long skewers for a fun treat.  They freeze beautifully and certainly are delicious.Really pretty and oh so tasty - I didn't use nearly as much sugar as called for - maybe 1 teaspoon total - This was just enough to give the grapes that crystal effect - they actually taste a bit like a sorbet.  Thanks for a fun idea.Awesome.  We really enjoyed this sugary frozen treat on a hot evening.  No need to even complete steps 4 and 5.  The grapes went straight into the freezer inside the resealable bag.  Easy and delicious!Agree that no sugar is needed.  I freeze them in snack-sized zip lock bags so so we can grab individual servings on the go (although you must eat them before they completely defrost or they will be mushy).Our grapes were extra sweet, so we didn't use sugar. This is something we actually do quite often. Just sticking them in the freezer and getting them out two hours later works well for snacks. Mmmmmm.

recipes.name: 10 Pound Cheesecake
recipes.description: "Cake pan full of sinful delight. The lemon juice does all the cooking"Cheers to the party-sized portion!  I had to make this immediately upon seeing the photo today. Used whipping cream from the refrigerated carton (on-hand), and it worked out wonderfully. This is a Restaurant-Style cheesecake for sure, only better. Used fresh, cut up, lightly sweetened strawberries on the side after chilling the cheesecake instead of using the strawberry pie filling.  Wonderful! Thank you for sharing the recipe.Good, but not my favorite. I prefer the recipe I already have. This was fantastic!! Made it the first time for 40 people & got rave reviews.  I didn't put the cherries on until a couple of hours before serving & my filling set up perfectly (don't know if holding off on the cherries had anything to do with that or not)!!!Excellent!!!! Oh my gosh was it ever good. We ended up serving it in bowls though as it didn't hold like a normal cheesecake does-don't worry-it's sooooo good you won't care!!!! YUM!!!! Thanks so much for sharing this awesome recipe!!!! Wonderful!! I hate cool-whip, so I substituted a pint of sweetened whipping cream. I also left off the cherry topping. It's a perfect alternatitive to painstakingly baking a cheesecake, especially in the summer.I now know why this is called 10 oound cheesecake.  It makes alot!  I topped my cheesecake with fresh strawberries.  This is a delicious recipe, thanks for sharing.  AMAZING AMAZING AMAZING. I have been trying to figure out how to replicate a recipe from a restaurant back home for "no-bake" cheesecake and this is almost IDENTICAL to it! I was thrilled w/ the huge portion too! :)  The lemon juice really adds some kick to this cheesecake. I wasn't sure if I would like it at first as I'm a very plain cheesecake lover, but this was amazing.  Next time I will add some crushed raspberries and cool whip to the top. YUMM!!!  Thanks for this great recipe!!Made this for a church gathering.  I used shredded coconut in the crust in place of the sugar and also added crushed walnuts.  Excellent.  Very easy to make and has a wonderful presence.  Thanks for posting it.

recipes.name: "Million Dollar" Chinese Cabbage Salad
recipes.description: "This recipe is ALWAYS a hit...with kids too! I used to call it my 'Million Dollar Salad' because buying the sesame seeds was so expensive. Now I buy the sesame seeds in bulk at a health food store and it's much more affordable."I have made this salad many times and it is a family favorite.  I cut oil down to 1/3 cup and use a 1/3 cup of Balsalmic vinegar.  I add chopped garlic, decrease sugar to 1/4 cup and add 5-6 packets of splenda.   This salad can also be made with Romaine lettuce and cranberries instead of cabbage for a little holiday flare.Good salad, a little sweet for my taste though.  I will definitely try it again, but will modify the amount of sugar.My whole family loves it!  Here are my modifications: I cut the sugar in 1/2.   My kids are not fans of onion so I omit them or put them on the side.  For a bit more flavor I like a bit of chopped fresh flat leaf parsley and shredded carrot(2T) which makes this salad even more vibrant looking.    A tip I'd like to share is to add about 1/2 tsp. sesame oil.  This gives a wonderful flavor.  The  dressing will  emulsify and not seperate once it's cold so chill it and whisk again before pouring on.   I like to pour the dressing about 15 minutes before eating or the ramen is too crunchy for me! :)I've added chunk cooked chicken breasts, Pinneapple and sometimes mandarin orangesMy mom used to make this when I was a kid. It is an awesome salad for either every day or to bring to a potluck.I emulsified the dressing so that it wouldn't separate overnight as I knew I'd be using the leftover dressing. Otherwise I followed the directions as written, only I keep the crunchy bits as a topping at the last minute instead of mixing in as we can't eat the whole salad in one sitting. Thanks for sharing your recipe!Great recipe.  Family loved it.  Making it again tonight.We are diabetic and looking for new and different recipes that can be tailored to our diet concerns.  I thought that I would try this one.  It was great.  I did have to make substations of course.  Splenda for the sugar and I did not use the raman noodles.  I did up the nuts a bit.  Hubby loved it and I may add more green onion.  Hubby wanted to try some chopped water chestnuts.  Thank you for sharing.

recipes.name: "Million Dollar" Chinese Cabbage Salad
recipes.description: "This recipe is ALWAYS a hit...with kids too! I used to call it my 'Million Dollar Salad' because buying the sesame seeds was so expensive. Now I buy the sesame seeds in bulk at a health food store and it's much more affordable."I have made this salad many times and it is a family favorite.  I cut oil down to 1/3 cup and use a 1/3 cup of Balsalmic vinegar.  I add chopped garlic, decrease sugar to 1/4 cup and add 5-6 packets of splenda.   This salad can also be made with Romaine lettuce and cranberries instead of cabbage for a little holiday flare.Good salad, a little sweet for my taste though.  I will definitely try it again, but will modify the amount of sugar.My whole family loves it!  Here are my modifications: I cut the sugar in 1/2.   My kids are not fans of onion so I omit them or put them on the side.  For a bit more flavor I like a bit of chopped fresh flat leaf parsley and shredded carrot(2T) which makes this salad even more vibrant looking.    A tip I'd like to share is to add about 1/2 tsp. sesame oil.  This gives a wonderful flavor.  The  dressing will  emulsify and not seperate once it's cold so chill it and whisk again before pouring on.   I like to pour the dressing about 15 minutes before eating or the ramen is too crunchy for me! :)I've added chunk cooked chicken breasts, Pinneapple and sometimes mandarin orangesMy mom used to make this when I was a kid. It is an awesome salad for either every day or to bring to a potluck.I emulsified the dressing so that it wouldn't separate overnight as I knew I'd be using the leftover dressing. Otherwise I followed the directions as written, only I keep the crunchy bits as a topping at the last minute instead of mixing in as we can't eat the whole salad in one sitting. Thanks for sharing your recipe!Great recipe.  Family loved it.  Making it again tonight.We are diabetic and looking for new and different recipes that can be tailored to our diet concerns.  I thought that I would try this one.  It was great.  I did have to make substations of course.  Splenda for the sugar and I did not use the raman noodles.  I did up the nuts a bit.  Hubby loved it and I may add more green onion.  Hubby wanted to try some chopped water chestnuts.  Thank you for sharing.

recipes.name: Applesauce Pumpkin Bread
recipes.description: "This yummy family tradition started when buying the kids their pumpkins. Each of the kids got one to make their jack o'lanterns. Mama got one to cook! Friends and family usually enjoy this treat. Tweak it to fit your family as I do mine! Enjoy with confectioners' sugar on top or cream cheese frosting!"Made half the recipe and used half splenda. Turned out perfectly as muffins. Pumpkn pie lke spice flavor and moist, not gooey.This was a hit! Moist and light, with a sweet and spicy flavor :) I left out the mace, chocolate, and confectioners' sugar, and used a 2 quart baking dish (9 x 13 inch pan).Delicious, moist and didn't last!!! I ended up making 3 batches because it never would have made it to our Easter gathering. I thought I would try this for a change from pumpkin pie this Easter. Everyone Loved it. I wasn't sure at first about adding the semisweet chips but my daughter insisted and the little hint of chips was prefect. I left out the walnuts. I didn't have any ginger, clove or mace in the cupboard so I substituted for 2tsp of pumpkin pie spice. I am going to make it again this weekend for an other dinner gathering.This was very easy and very good.  I followed the recipe, except that I did not have mace but instead used 1/4 teaspoon nutmeg and 1/4 teaspoon allspice.  I added the optional chocolate chips but next time I would probably leave those out, just my personal preference.  By all means give this recipe a try.  The measurements and cooking time were spot on.  Thanks Virginia Ann for sharing your recipe.

recipes.name: 10-Minute Tomato Basil Salad
recipes.description: "Perfect for summer, delightfully delicious!"When I make this salad, I like to throw in a clove of fresh minced garlic. If you can stand it, throw this together and let it sit for an hour. NOTE: This is also just as good with a quality balsamic vinegar.Very nice, easy and light.  We loved this!Very simple, fast, and tasty.

recipes.name: 100% Whole Wheat Pancakes
recipes.description: "These come out very light and fluffy and are full of whole grain. My kids love them! If you like blueberries, throw a few on top before flipping the cake :)"

recipes.name: 100% Fruit "Cake"
recipes.description: "This cake was a hit with the children and parents at our two-year-old's birthday party.  It is perfect for raw, vegan, gluten/wheat-free, refined sugar-free diets (and children who don't need sugar!).  This cake was inspired by a 100% watermelon cake we had the year before."laysho!Made it for my friends little brother, hes 6 and loved it. Thanks for the recipe :3

recipes.name: 100 Percent Whole Wheat Bread
recipes.description: "Nice soft whole wheat bread with added grains. Makes a 2 large loaves. Double recipe for 3 smaller loaves."So delicious!! I couldn't find vital wheat gluten, so I omitted it, but it turned out great anyway. I also added more water in the kneading process. Great recipe, thanks for sharing!should have read the reviews first, but the water/flour ratio is off.  I am somewhat new at bread and kept thinking that I was not doing something right, but it was the ratios.This is great bread! I had to make some omissions based on what I had handy (no sesame, sunflower seeds or coconut oil. I tossed in some wheat germ instead - otherwise followed the recipe except for the shape...I got 6 sandwich rolls and 1 large bunny loaf out of this. Thanks for the recipe!One detail:  If you've had breast cancer that was estrogen-receptor positive, you should avoid flax seed and flax meal.  Either leave them out, or add more of the other seeds.Let me preface this by saying I am just starting to bake bread.  It is very difficult to find a recipe with 100% whole wheat.  The only modification I made to this recipe was to add an additional 4 Tbls water as I could not get my dough to form without. I just pulled it out of the oven and my husband and I both enjoyed a slice.  Great flavor and not too dense.  Next time I am going to try using just vitamin C and omit at least some of the wheat gluten.  Thanks for sharing a great recipe for healthy bread!This was my first time attempting bread and it came out great!  I didn't have the flax seeds (added a bit extra flax seed meal) or the coconut oil (substituted toasted sesame oil) and needed to add a bit more water to get the dough to form. Tried to use my kitchenaid mixer but ended up just making it smoke -- so did all kneading by hand.  I didn't knead for full times because I got tired, but it still came out great.   The bread was a big hit and now I'm going to use it for french toast.The bread was tasty and good for sandwiches but the flour / water content was off. I used more water and approximately 5 1/2 c flour.The bread turned out beautiful.  I did have to use 2 cups of water  instead of 1/34.  Also when you cover it, don't put saran wrap on it, it will stick. It was so good.  I will make it again.

recipes.name: 10 Pound Cheesecake
recipes.description: "Cake pan full of sinful delight. The lemon juice does all the cooking"Cheers to the party-sized portion!  I had to make this immediately upon seeing the photo today. Used whipping cream from the refrigerated carton (on-hand), and it worked out wonderfully. This is a Restaurant-Style cheesecake for sure, only better. Used fresh, cut up, lightly sweetened strawberries on the side after chilling the cheesecake instead of using the strawberry pie filling.  Wonderful! Thank you for sharing the recipe.Good, but not my favorite. I prefer the recipe I already have. This was fantastic!! Made it the first time for 40 people & got rave reviews.  I didn't put the cherries on until a couple of hours before serving & my filling set up perfectly (don't know if holding off on the cherries had anything to do with that or not)!!!Excellent!!!! Oh my gosh was it ever good. We ended up serving it in bowls though as it didn't hold like a normal cheesecake does-don't worry-it's sooooo good you won't care!!!! YUM!!!! Thanks so much for sharing this awesome recipe!!!! Wonderful!! I hate cool-whip, so I substituted a pint of sweetened whipping cream. I also left off the cherry topping. It's a perfect alternatitive to painstakingly baking a cheesecake, especially in the summer.I now know why this is called 10 oound cheesecake.  It makes alot!  I topped my cheesecake with fresh strawberries.  This is a delicious recipe, thanks for sharing.  AMAZING AMAZING AMAZING. I have been trying to figure out how to replicate a recipe from a restaurant back home for "no-bake" cheesecake and this is almost IDENTICAL to it! I was thrilled w/ the huge portion too! :)  The lemon juice really adds some kick to this cheesecake. I wasn't sure if I would like it at first as I'm a very plain cheesecake lover, but this was amazing.  Next time I will add some crushed raspberries and cool whip to the top. YUMM!!!  Thanks for this great recipe!!Made this for a church gathering.  I used shredded coconut in the crust in place of the sugar and also added crushed walnuts.  Excellent.  Very easy to make and has a wonderful presence.  Thanks for posting it.

recipes.name: #1 Pumpkin Spice Cookies
recipes.description: "Delectable sponge-like cookies that are sweet and remind you of holiday seasons all year long!"Yummy, moist and healthy! I didn't have apple butter so per another user's suggestion, I used applesauce instead. These turned out great! The spices are just the right amount. And only 1 point if you're a WW person :)i love pumpkin! this was average, expected more. if you think  of it as little drops of cake instead of a cookie, you may enjoy it better. i looked up a 5 star cream cheese frosting to add some flavor and it was better. think i'll rename these "iced pumpkin puffs"! probably will try another recipe though....just being honest!These were pretty good. I made half of the batch with nuts, the other without. I personally liked them better without the nuts, but that's just because I'm not a big fan of walnuts. I really liked the fluffy texture. These are lightly, not overly spiced. For some reason every time I make pumpkin cookies I have an allergic skin reaction so I have to wear latex gloves :-P Edit: Beware! These cookies get very sticky on the surface after a while. It doesn't affect the taste, but it is kind of weird.I thought they were pretty good, but they were kind of mushy on the inside. I would add a minute to the bake time, but besides that, they were fine.I LOVE these!  I thought they might be a little heavy on the spices, but the balance was perfect, and I love the slightly different texture the oats add.  These will be in my favorite cookie file for sure!  I didn't add the nuts, no one here likes nuts, but the light muffin like texture is perfect!TASTEY!! It's the end of August and I pulled out a pkg of pumpkin puree (AR's Pumpkin Puree) I had in the freezer... and then goodness happened:) As I was adding the spices I got an excited flutter in my stomach reminding me of Fall and all things autumn. Thanks for an excellent recipe. I changed a couple things out of necessity(didn't have on hand or allergy) but I'm sure it didn't change the main objective or flavor/texture, it came out as described. Changes: whole wheat instead of all purpose flour, allspice instead of pumpkin pie spice, applesauce instead of apple butter and chocolate chips instead of walnuts(allergy). Very good recipe!!!I doubled this recipe and it lasted one day with the family and friends.  Everyone wanted the recipe.  will diffently be a keeper in my recipe book!!!  Next time I might try using a cream cheese icing, but then again maybe not.  The are soft and delicious the way they are!very good and much easier to make then expected! Was also worried that they may be too spicy but they turned out perfect, only baked them for 9 mins and they were delish! Will make over and over again!

recipes.name: "Pantry Raid" Chicken Enchilada Casserole
recipes.description: "I made this recipe up one night when I had no idea what to do with a pound and a half of chicken tenderloins. It came out so well that my husband and I finished off the leftovers the next day and we are not usually leftover eaters. I am gluten-free so I used gluten-free cornbread mix. You will definitely enjoy it!"Yum.  OH!  I made this as a one-dish crockpot recipe and it was delicious.  I used chicken breasts, not tenders, adding them raw to the seasoned tomato sauce mixture and cooking it all on LO for 3.5 hrs (less for tenders).  After adding in the rest and topping with the corn muffin mix, I cooked on HI for 1.5 hours.  Next time I'll add diced onion (1 sm) and 1-2 cloves minced garlic to the tomato sauce mixture, but even as is, this was great, and a keeper.  Thanks for posting!This recipe would've been great if I had followed the original recipe.  I followed the review that recommended I cook it in the crock pot.  After 5 hours, it was complete mush!  We dipped tortilla chips in it, but it was a little much to call it a main dish.  Next time I will follow the original recipe.  The flavors were great, but a little sweet.  I may look for a corn bread mix without sugar.This was so simple and fantastic!  I added red bell pepper, onion, and minced garlic; and substituted Costco rotisserie chicken pulled off the bone.  oohlala!This was easy and delicious. I didn't even  brown the chicken first. Just simmered it with the tomato sauce. My family loved it.I made this last night and thought it was great! I added some sauteed ingredients (a large minced onion, corn, chopped mixed bell pepper strips). I also added a can of Ro-Tel diced tomatoes and green chiles. I omitted the water and just used the juice from the Ro-Tel can. Lastly, I added about a teaspoon of cumin. I know it sounds like a lot of changes but at the end of the day, the basis of this recipe is great. Don't be afraid of the 1 1/2 T of chili powder. I thought it would be quite spicy with that much but it wasn't at all and I added the Ro-Tel too! Don't be afraid to continue what started this recipe in the first place...the pantry raid!This was awesome.  I would give it 10 stars if I could.  For me this is pure comfort food; and it is so easy.  I cheated and used shredded rotisserie chicken, light cream cheese and substituted my customized Grandmother's Buttermilk Cornbread recipe with corn and jalapeños from this site instead of the cornbread mix.  So it was a super fast dinner.   Thanks for sharing a great recipe.This made a delicious and hearty meal. The only changes that I made were to use 2 cans of chicken, browned with onions and a tsp. minced garlic.  My family loved this one. I will definitely make it again.I made this tonight, and I didn't change one thing.  My husband asked for seconds and he is a picky eater. I loved the corn bread topping.

recipes.name: "Million Dollar" Chinese Cabbage Salad
recipes.description: "This recipe is ALWAYS a hit...with kids too! I used to call it my 'Million Dollar Salad' because buying the sesame seeds was so expensive. Now I buy the sesame seeds in bulk at a health food store and it's much more affordable."I have made this salad many times and it is a family favorite.  I cut oil down to 1/3 cup and use a 1/3 cup of Balsalmic vinegar.  I add chopped garlic, decrease sugar to 1/4 cup and add 5-6 packets of splenda.   This salad can also be made with Romaine lettuce and cranberries instead of cabbage for a little holiday flare.Good salad, a little sweet for my taste though.  I will definitely try it again, but will modify the amount of sugar.My whole family loves it!  Here are my modifications: I cut the sugar in 1/2.   My kids are not fans of onion so I omit them or put them on the side.  For a bit more flavor I like a bit of chopped fresh flat leaf parsley and shredded carrot(2T) which makes this salad even more vibrant looking.    A tip I'd like to share is to add about 1/2 tsp. sesame oil.  This gives a wonderful flavor.  The  dressing will  emulsify and not seperate once it's cold so chill it and whisk again before pouring on.   I like to pour the dressing about 15 minutes before eating or the ramen is too crunchy for me! :)I've added chunk cooked chicken breasts, Pinneapple and sometimes mandarin orangesMy mom used to make this when I was a kid. It is an awesome salad for either every day or to bring to a potluck.I emulsified the dressing so that it wouldn't separate overnight as I knew I'd be using the leftover dressing. Otherwise I followed the directions as written, only I keep the crunchy bits as a topping at the last minute instead of mixing in as we can't eat the whole salad in one sitting. Thanks for sharing your recipe!Great recipe.  Family loved it.  Making it again tonight.We are diabetic and looking for new and different recipes that can be tailored to our diet concerns.  I thought that I would try this one.  It was great.  I did have to make substations of course.  Splenda for the sugar and I did not use the raman noodles.  I did up the nuts a bit.  Hubby loved it and I may add more green onion.  Hubby wanted to try some chopped water chestnuts.  Thank you for sharing.

recipes.name: "Spa"ctacular Frozen Grapes
recipes.description: "These grapes were served to me after a massage at my local spa. This recipe is perfect as an after-school snack, a simple appetizer at parties, or a sweet treat before bed. Substitute Splenda® for the sugar if you like! Can be kept in a sealed bag in the freezer for several months.""Spectacular" little recipe! Ya just gotta love it when a few items you have laying around the kitchen turn into something a little extra special...  I've frozen fruit before, but never grapes. And while they're delicious with or without sugar - that addition gave regular 'ol grapes a little pizzaz.  I did use less sugar than called for and opted for Spenda which made the amount even less.  This was so easy and tasted oh so good - very nice little treat without any guilt.No sweetener necessary, even for kids' tastes, and certainly "spa"-healthier without! Frozen grapes are awesome just by themselves... They're like little natural popsicles!You can also use Sugar Free Jello for an added flavor.Never mind the sugar and put them on long skewers for a fun treat.  They freeze beautifully and certainly are delicious.Really pretty and oh so tasty - I didn't use nearly as much sugar as called for - maybe 1 teaspoon total - This was just enough to give the grapes that crystal effect - they actually taste a bit like a sorbet.  Thanks for a fun idea.Awesome.  We really enjoyed this sugary frozen treat on a hot evening.  No need to even complete steps 4 and 5.  The grapes went straight into the freezer inside the resealable bag.  Easy and delicious!Agree that no sugar is needed.  I freeze them in snack-sized zip lock bags so so we can grab individual servings on the go (although you must eat them before they completely defrost or they will be mushy).Our grapes were extra sweet, so we didn't use sugar. This is something we actually do quite often. Just sticking them in the freezer and getting them out two hours later works well for snacks. Mmmmmm.

recipes.name: (Gluten Free) Magic Cookie Bars
recipes.description:
"I did a combination of two recipes, peanut butter cookies with three ingredients and magic cookie bars. My brother-in-law loves magic cookie bars but is now gluten-free. I have been trying to come up with desserts for him so he doesn't feel left out. This is an amazing dessert and will stay fresh for days...if they last that long in your house! Perfect for Passover - no flour!"I absolutely appreciate that someone took the time to find a gluten-free alternative crust to these bars. Thank you for offering an idea I would never have thought of on my own!

After having made them, I believe that the peanut butter cookie base makes the squares far far too sweet and rich, and the peanut taste totally overpowers the rest of the nuts in the bars. At least for my tastes, anyway. My husband and his dad liked them, but they could only eat one square at a sitting.

My oven sucks, so I only realized later that the cookie base didn't cook/set as much as I would have liked. I would recommend longer than 8 minutes, and at a higher temp to at least set the PB.

**It was easy to make and prep.** If you don't normally have these ingredients in your cupboard, you can save money by only buying the amount you need in the bulk section of your grocery store.

I am going to try to find a gluten-free crust that is more like the original base I knew and loved when I ate gluten. Something less overpowering than the peanut butter.

All in all, nice to be able to make something to take to holiday parties that was gluten-free, but not many people ate them, and no one took a second.I make these for My Brother in Law who is Gluten Free. You can "tweak" the recipe and add tons of different kinds of nuts and chocolate candies and carmel on top. I switch it up all the time. Works best with parchment paper in the bottom of the pan. Enjoy!

recipes.name: "Pantry Raid" Chicken Enchilada Casserole
recipes.description: "I made this recipe up one night when I had no idea what to do with a pound and a half of chicken tenderloins. It came out so well that my husband and I finished off the leftovers the next day and we are not usually leftover eaters. I am gluten-free so I used gluten-free cornbread mix. You will definitely enjoy it!"Yum.  OH!  I made this as a one-dish crockpot recipe and it was delicious.  I used chicken breasts, not tenders, adding them raw to the seasoned tomato sauce mixture and cooking it all on LO for 3.5 hrs (less for tenders).  After adding in the rest and topping with the corn muffin mix, I cooked on HI for 1.5 hours.  Next time I'll add diced onion (1 sm) and 1-2 cloves minced garlic to the tomato sauce mixture, but even as is, this was great, and a keeper.  Thanks for posting!This recipe would've been great if I had followed the original recipe.  I followed the review that recommended I cook it in the crock pot.  After 5 hours, it was complete mush!  We dipped tortilla chips in it, but it was a little much to call it a main dish.  Next time I will follow the original recipe.  The flavors were great, but a little sweet.  I may look for a corn bread mix without sugar.This was so simple and fantastic!  I added red bell pepper, onion, and minced garlic; and substituted Costco rotisserie chicken pulled off the bone.  oohlala!This was easy and delicious. I didn't even  brown the chicken first. Just simmered it with the tomato sauce. My family loved it.I made this last night and thought it was great! I added some sauteed ingredients (a large minced onion, corn, chopped mixed bell pepper strips). I also added a can of Ro-Tel diced tomatoes and green chiles. I omitted the water and just used the juice from the Ro-Tel can. Lastly, I added about a teaspoon of cumin. I know it sounds like a lot of changes but at the end of the day, the basis of this recipe is great. Don't be afraid of the 1 1/2 T of chili powder. I thought it would be quite spicy with that much but it wasn't at all and I added the Ro-Tel too! Don't be afraid to continue what started this recipe in the first place...the pantry raid!This was awesome.  I would give it 10 stars if I could.  For me this is pure comfort food; and it is so easy.  I cheated and used shredded rotisserie chicken, light cream cheese and substituted my customized Grandmother's Buttermilk Cornbread recipe with corn and jalapeños from this site instead of the cornbread mix.  So it was a super fast dinner.   Thanks for sharing a great recipe.This made a delicious and hearty meal. The only changes that I made were to use 2 cans of chicken, browned with onions and a tsp. minced garlic.  My family loved this one. I will definitely make it again.I made this tonight, and I didn't change one thing.  My husband asked for seconds and he is a picky eater. I loved the corn bread topping.
